Indexes ?
----------

Indexes are a feature that can drastically speed up your queries.
An index can speed up our find, update or delete queries.

Conside a find query

db.products.find({seller :"Vijay"})
db.products.find({email :"vijayvaidya99@gmail.com"})

By default if i don't have an index on seller set mongodb will go ahead and do a collection scan. 
It means that mongodb to fulfill this query will go through the entire collection.
look at every single document and see it seller equals vijay.

We can create the index for the seller key of the products collection here.
It is the values of field which you created that index and every item or value in the index has a pointer
to the full document it belongs to.
Now this allows mongodb to do a indexscan to fulfill this query, which means it sees that for seller such 
an index exists and it therefore simply goes to that seller index and can quickly jump to the right values
because there, unlike for collection it knows that the value is sorted by that key.
It direclt jumps into the right values because there unlike the collection it knows that the values are
sorted by key.

__________
|Prodcuts | 
|Seller   | 
|Indexe   |
|_________|
|"Anna"   |
|"Chris"  |
|"Manu"   |
|"Manu"   |
|"Max"    |
|"Max"    |
|"Vijay"  |
|_________|

Don't use too many Indexes because though it will fast the find queries but insertion becomes slow.
If we add a new document to a collection we also have to add a new element to the index.
If we have a 10 indexes for your documents in your collection and you have to update all the 10 indexes
for every insert,then you might quickly run into issue becuase we have to do lots of work for all these 
fields, for every insert and for every update too.

//--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

db.collectioName.explain().find({dob.age:{$gt:60}})

explain() => it use to analyze how it executed query.
it gives some detail description of what mongodb did and how it derived our results.

like :
 "winning plan" : {
    "stage":"COLLSCAN",          // query resulted with collection scan
    "filter" : {
        "dob.age":{             // filter query
            "$gt:60
        }
    },
    "direction" : "forward"
},
"serverInfo" : {
    host,port,version...
}

it works for find,update, delete not for insert.

//------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

db.collectioName.explain("executionStats").find({dob.age:{$gt:60}})

// output : 

"executionStats" :{
    "executionSuccess" : true,
    "executionTimeMillis" : 5,           // time taken to execute query
    "nReturned" : 2122                   // total docs returned
    "totalDocsExamined" : 5000          // Out of 5000 docs
    .....
}

//------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

db.collectioName.createIndex({"dob.age":1}) // it will create index on age field in ascending order

Indexes Behind the Scenes
What does createIndex() do in detail?

Whilst we can't really see the index, you can think of the index as a simple list of values + pointers to the original document.

Something like this (for the "age" field):

(29, "address in memory/ collection a1")

(30, "address in memory/ collection a2")

(33, "address in memory/ collection a3")

The documents in the collection would be at the "addresses" a1, a2 and a3. The order does not have to match the order in the index (and most likely, it indeed won't).

The important thing is that the index items are ordered (ascending or descending - depending on how you created the index). createIndex({age: 1}) creates an index with ascending sorting, createIndex({age: -1}) creates one with descending sorting.

MongoDB is now able to quickly find a fitting document when you filter for its age as it has a sorted list. Sorted lists are way quicker to search because you can skip entire ranges (and don't have to look at every single document).

Additionally, sorting (via sort(...)) will also be sped up because you already have a sorted list. Of course this is only true when sorting for the age.

//------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Understanding Index Restrictions

If you have a query that will return a large portion or the majority of your documents an index can actually 
be a slower bcoz you have then extra step to go through entire index list and then you have to go to collection
and get all these documents.

if you have a queries that regularly return the majority or all of your documents index will not really helpful.
it might even slow down the execution.

We save the step to going to the index


//------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

db.collectioName.createIndex({"dob.age":1,gender :1}) // it will create compund index on age and gender field in ascending order

it does not create the two indexes it creates one index where every element is connected value.
here it will create the pairs of age and gender.
for e.g : 30 male, 30 male, 30 female, 31 male, 31 female and so on. in the index list

db.collectioName.explain().find({dob.age:35,gender:"male"})

//------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

db.collectioName.createIndex({email:1},{unique :true})// it will create index on email ascending with unique value of email

